.TH "super" "1" "April 2026" ""
.SH NAME
super \(em process data with SuperSQL queries
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]super\f[R] [\f[I]options\f[R]] \f[I]command\f[R]
.PP
\f[B]super\f[R] [\f[I]options\f[R]] [\f[B]\-c\f[R] \f[I]query\f[R]]
[\f[I]file\f[R] \&...]
.SH DESCRIPTION
\f[B]super\f[R] executes SuperSQL queries against data in a variety of
formats.
It operates either as a standalone query engine (detached from any
database) or as the entry point to a hierarchy of sub\-commands for
managing SuperDB databases, inspecting query compilation, and accessing
developer tooling.
.PP
When invoked without a sub\-command, \f[B]super\f[R] runs the SuperDB
query engine against the specified input files or standard input.
Input may also be specified within the query itself using a
\f[B]from\f[R] operator or a SQL \f[CR]FROM\f[R] clause.
If no query is given, inputs are scanned and serialized to the output
format unchanged, providing a convenient format\-conversion tool.
.PP
If no input is specified, the query receives a single \f[CR]null\f[R]
value, analogous to SQL\(cqs default input of a single empty row,
enabling use as a calculator or for standalone expressions.
.PP
Input paths may be local file paths, \f[CR]\-\f[R] for standard input,
or HTTP, HTTPS, or S3 URLs.
When multiple input files are specified they are processed in order as
if concatenated in a single \f[B]from\f[R] clause.
.SS Format Detection
\f[B]super\f[R] automatically infers input formats from file extensions
(\f[CR].json\f[R], \f[CR].parquet\f[R], \f[CR].sup\f[R], etc.)
or by reading and parsing a sample of the data.
Use \f[CR]\-i\f[R] to override format detection; when \f[CR]\-i\f[R] is
specified all input files must share the same format.
The \f[CR]line\f[R] format cannot be auto\-detected and always requires
\f[CR]\-i line\f[R] or an explicit \f[CR](format line)\f[R] option in a
\f[B]from\f[R] operator.
.PP
Parquet and CSUP require seekable input and cannot be read from standard
input.
.SS Output
Output is written to standard output by default, or to the file or
directory specified by \f[CR]\-o\f[R].
When writing to a terminal, the default output format is SUP; otherwise
it is BSUP.
These defaults may be overridden with \f[CR]\-f\f[R], \f[CR]\-s\f[R], or
\f[CR]\-S\f[R].
.PP
For schema\-rigid output formats (Arrow, Parquet), all values must
conform to a single schema.
Use the \f[B]fuse\f[R] or \f[B]blend\f[R] operators to unify
heterogeneous types, or use \f[CR]\-split\f[R] to write one file per
distinct type.
.SS Errors
Fatal errors (e.g., file not found, filesystem full) cause
\f[B]super\f[R] to exit immediately.
Runtime errors produced by the query itself do not halt execution;
instead they appear as first\-class error values interleaved with normal
output.
These can be detected and filtered using the \f[B]is_error\f[R]
function.
.SS Debugging
Run \f[B]super\f[R] with \f[CR]\-C\f[R] to compile and display a query
in canonical form without executing it.
This is useful for understanding how abbreviated SuperSQL syntax expands
into full pipe\-query form.
The \f[B]debug\f[R] operator may be inserted anywhere in a query
pipeline to trace intermediate values to standard error.
